{"title_page": "Jyotirmayananda Saraswati", "text_new": "<!-- Please do not remove or change this AfD message until the discussion has been closed. -->\n{{Article for deletion/dated|page=Jyotirmayananda Saraswati|timestamp=20200417010826|year=2020|month=April|day=17|substed=yes|help=off}}\n<!-- Once discussion is closed, please place on talk page: {{Old AfD multi|page=Jyotirmayananda Saraswati|date=17 April 2020|result='''keep'''}} -->\n<!-- End of AfD message, feel free to edit beyond this point -->\n{{nofootnotes|date=February 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=February 2020}}\n[[File:Swami Jyotirmayananda GB.jpg|thumb|alt=Jyotirmayananda Saraswati 2010|Jyotirmayananda Saraswati 2010.]]'''Jyotirmayananda Saraswati''' (born 3 February 1931) is an [[India]]n teacher of Vedanta, spiritual [[Hindu]] philosophy, and author of over 40 books on [[Vedanta]], [[Yoga]] and several other topics<ref>https://www.dlshq.org/saints/jyotir.htm</ref>. He was a disciple of [[Sivananda Saraswati]], and served as a religious professor at [[Yoga-Vedanta Forest Academy]], at the [[Sivananda Ashram]] in [[Rishikesh]] for nine years. Jyotirmayananda is president of Yoga Research Foundation in [[Miami, Florida]]<ref>https://shop.yrf.org/about-swamiji/</ref><ref>https://www.encyclopedia.com/science/encyclopedias-almanacs-transcripts-and-maps/yoga-research-foundation-inc</ref>.\n\n==Publications==\nJyotirmayananda has written over 50 books emphasizing yoga philosophy in everyday life, helping people understand how to work towards a goal of attaining [[self-realization]].\n\nTitles include such popular titles as:\nAdvice To Householders\nAdvice To Students\nApplied Yoga\nConcentration And Meditation\nMystic Pathways Through The Bible\nMysticism Of Hindu Gods And Goddesses\nSex-Sublimation, Truth And Nonviolence\nThe Art Of Positive Feeling\nYoga Can Change Your Life\n\nHe is also the author of the monthly International Yoga Guide magazine which is published locally at his ashram.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.yrf.org/ Yoga Research Foundation]\n*[http://www.dlshq.org/saints/jyotir.htm Saint Reference]\n*[http://yogaresearch.podomatic.com/ Current Podcasts by Swami Jyotirmayananda]\n*[http://www.yogachicago.com/jan03/resolutions.shtml Temple of Kriya Yoga Chicago reference]\n*[http://www.sivanandaonline.org/public_html/?cmd=displaysection&section_id=1370 Divine Life Society (Sivananda's official site)]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jyotirmayananda Saraswati}}\n[[Category:1931 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:20th-century Hindu religious leaders]]\n[[Category:21st-century Hindu religious leaders]]\n[[Category:Indian Hindu religious leaders]]\n[[Category:Hindu writers]]\n[[Category:Advaita Vedanta]]\n", "text_old": "<!-- Please do not remove or change this AfD message until the discussion has been closed. -->\n{{Article for deletion/dated|page=Jyotirmayananda Saraswati|timestamp=20200417010826|year=2020|month=April|day=17|substed=yes|help=off}}\n<!-- Once discussion is closed, please place on talk page: {{Old AfD multi|page=Jyotirmayananda Saraswati|date=17 April 2020|result='''keep'''}} -->\n<!-- End of AfD message, feel free to edit beyond this point -->\n{{nofootnotes|date=February 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=February 2020}}\n[[File:Swami Jyotirmayananda GB.jpg|thumb|alt=Jyotirmayananda Saraswati 2010|Jyotirmayananda Saraswati 2010.]]'''Jyotirmayananda Saraswati''' (born 3 February 1931) is an [[India]]n teacher of Vedanta, spiritual [[Hindu]] philosophy, and author of over 40 books on [[Vedanta]], [[Yoga]] and several other topics<ref>https://www.dlshq.org/saints/jyotir.htm</ref>. He was a disciple of [[Sivananda Saraswati]], and served as a religious professor at [[Yoga-Vedanta Forest Academy]], at the [[Sivananda Ashram]] in [[Rishikesh]] for nine years. Jyotirmayananda is president of Yoga Research Foundation in [[Miami, Florida]]<ref>https://shop.yrf.org/about-swamiji/</ref>.\n\n==Publications==\nJyotirmayananda has written over 50 books emphasizing yoga philosophy in everyday life, helping people understand how to work towards a goal of attaining [[self-realization]].\n\nTitles include such popular titles as:\nAdvice To Householders\nAdvice To Students\nApplied Yoga\nConcentration And Meditation\nMystic Pathways Through The Bible\nMysticism Of Hindu Gods And Goddesses\nSex-Sublimation, Truth And Nonviolence\nThe Art Of Positive Feeling\nYoga Can Change Your Life\n\nHe is also the author of the monthly International Yoga Guide magazine which is published locally at his ashram.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.yrf.org/ Yoga Research Foundation]\n*[http://www.dlshq.org/saints/jyotir.htm Saint Reference]\n*[http://yogaresearch.podomatic.com/ Current Podcasts by Swami Jyotirmayananda]\n*[http://www.yogachicago.com/jan03/resolutions.shtml Temple of Kriya Yoga Chicago reference]\n*[http://www.sivanandaonline.org/public_html/?cmd=displaysection&section_id=1370 Divine Life Society (Sivananda's official site)]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jyotirmayananda Saraswati}}\n[[Category:1931 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:20th-century Hindu religious leaders]]\n[[Category:21st-century Hindu religious leaders]]\n[[Category:Indian Hindu religious leaders]]\n[[Category:Hindu writers]]\n[[Category:Advaita Vedanta]]\n", "name_user": "Eternal Father", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jyotirmayananda_Saraswati"}
{"title_page": "Scooby-Doo! Legend of the Phantosaur", "text_new": "{{Infobox television\n| show_name            = Scooby-Doo! Legend of the Phantosaur\n| image                = Scooby-Doo! Legend of the Phantosaur.png\n| image_size           = \n| image_alt            = \n| caption              = DVD Cover\n| genre                = \n| creator              = \n| based_on             = {{Based on|''[[Scooby-Doo]]''|[[Joe Ruby]] and [[Ken Spears]]}}\n| writer               = [[Doug Langdale]]\n| screenplay           = \n| story                = \n| director             = [[Ethan Spaulding]]\n| starring             = {{unbulleted list|[[Frank Welker]]|[[Matthew Lillard]]|[[Mindy Cohn]]|[[Grey DeLisle]]|[[Cathy Cavadini]]|[[John DiMaggio]]|[[Michael Gough (voice actor)|Michael Gough]]|[[Matthew Gray Gubler]]|[[Finola Hughes]]|[[Maulik Pancholy]]|[[Kevin Michael Richardson]]|[[Fred Willard]]|[[Dave Wittenberg]]|[[Gwendoline Yeo]]}}\n| narrated             = \n| theme_music_composer = [[Robert J. Kral]]\n| country              = United States\n| language             = English\n| num_episodes         = \n| producer             = [[Spike Brandt]]<br />[[Tony Cervone]]\n| editor               = Damon P. Yoches\n| cinematography       = \n| runtime              = 75 minutes<ref name=\"amazon.com\"/>\n| company              = [[Warner Bros. Animation]]\n| distributor          = [[Warner Home Video]] (DVD)<br />[[Warner Bros. Television]] (TV)\n| budget               = \n| network              = [[Cartoon Network]]\n| first_aired          = {{Film date|TV=y|2011|9|6}}<ref name=\"amazon.com\"/>\n| last_aired           = \n| website              = \n}}\n'''''Scooby-Doo! Legend of the Phantosaur''''' is a 2011 [[direct-to-DVD]] [[animation|animated]] [[comedy film|comedy]] [[mystery film]]; the sixteenth direct-to-video movie based upon the ''[[Scooby-Doo]]'' [[Saturday morning cartoon]]s, the film was released on September 6, 2011.<ref name=\"amazon.com\">{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/dp/B0055HK7D8|title=Amazon.com: Scooby-Doo! Legend of the Phantosaur|author=|date=|work=amazon.com}}</ref> It premiered on Cartoon Network on September 3, 2011.\n\n==Plot==\nThe Mystery Inc. gang travels to a remote town to stay at the La Serena Spa in New Mexico, to relax Shaggy after a scary experience in a haunted mansion left him screaming for a few hours afterward. There, they meet Mr. Hubley, who works at the spa. When Shaggy asks if there is anything to eat, Hubley says no, but there is a barbecue in town.\n\nThe gang goes to the barbecue, and all but Shaggy and Scooby-Doo go off to see the paleontological dig of Professor Svankmajer. Shaggy and Scooby are too full to walk right away. When they set out, a [[gila monster]] steals a biscuit from them, causing Scooby to go after it. He meets the Phantosaur (described as somewhat resembling an ''[[Appalachiosaurus]]'' by Professor Svankmajer) and runs away. Later, Shaggy and Scooby are chased by the Phantosaur and narrowly escape.\n\nMeanwhile, Professor Svankmajor shows the rest of the gang over the dig, and Velma meets Svankmajor's student, Winsor. She instantly sees him as a soul mate and they plan to go out on a date, to which Fred replies to Daphne, \"On our own for clue searching then.\"\n\nBack at the spa, Shaggy is in terrible shape after a fright. Mr. Hubley helps with aromatherapy, assisted by Scooby-Doo adding a Scooby Snack to the aromas. Shaggy becomes more calm, but freaks out again when Mr. Hubley tells them the legend of the Phantosaur, the ghost of a predatory dinosaur. The legend says the Phantosaur was summoned by Native Americans to drive out Spanish conquistadors, but it turned on them instead.\n\nHubley has an advanced hypnosis machine with a hologram projector. He hypnotizes Shaggy to become fearless and unstoppable when he heard the word \"bad,\" and to switch back to normal when he hears it again. Then he orders Shaggy to forget everything; unfortunately, Hubley himself is affected by the hypnosis and he can't remember the key word for Shaggy.\n\nDaphne, Fred, and Velma go back to the dig to look for clues, but Velma is so love struck that she's not much use. She misses an obvious clue about many footprints going to a part of the cave where Winsor says they never go because of the snakes that lurk in the lower cave levels.\n\nMeanwhile, Scooby and Shaggy go to an all-you-can-eat restaurant and start to eat it out of business. Then a biker gang comes in. Shaggy accidentally squirts the contents of a [[hot dog bun]] on one of the bikers, who angrily grabs him and tells him, \"Little buddy, this is gonna be bad.\" Suddenly, Shaggy is fearless. He knocks out the whole motorcycle gang and repels all their assaults on him. Then the gang leader, a large, muscly man named Tex, arrives and, taking an admitted liking to Shaggy, challenges him to a motorcycle race on Dead Man's curve. Shaggy confidently accepts, even though he's never ridden a motorcycle before. As Tex leaves the restaurant, he tells Shaggy that he won't kill Shaggy \"too bad.\". Suddenly back to normal, Shaggy is terrified of the challenge he has just accepted, and by what he has just done to the rest of the gang.\n\nThat night, Daphne decides to give him motorcycling lessons, because she drove a motorcycle when she was five. Shaggy and Tex have their motorcycle race as planned, and Shaggy hears \"bad\" just in time and almost wins, until a Phantosaur shows up and he thinks in his mind that the monster must think it's so \"bad,\" which is enough to make him cowardly again and get chased, but still miraculously wins the race.\n\nEventually, they figure out that there were two phantosaurs and they were robots. The culprits were two mining engineers who wanted the silver they found in the area, which they couldn't get to because of the paleontologists.\n\nOnce back at Hubley's they find the hologram projector gone and they get attacked by a pack of ''[[Velociraptor]]'' and a ghostly fire-breathing ''[[Tyrannosaurus]]''. They learn that it was Professor Svankmajer and Winsor, much to Velma's dismay. They had found a complete ''[[Allosaurus]]'' encased in quartz crystal, a beautiful and priceless find, and they wanted to keep it for themselves. They wanted to scare everyone off so they could dig it out and take it away. They disguised three other graduate students in velociraptor costumes, and created an original red Phantosaur with an advanced holographic projector (stolen from Hubley's hypnotism room) and paint-stripper devices that blasted super-heated air for the fire effects.\n\nWhile they are underground, the dynamite charges Svankmajor set to blast free the dinosaur crystal go off (because Daphne left a paint-stripper on and the heat lit the fuses). Shaggy's hypnotic bravery comes in again when Svankmejer comments on how \"bad\" the lower caverns are, and he flawlessly leads them toward the exit until Daphne praises him that he's \"not bad.\"  Scooby realizes the keyword but is unable to tell the rest of the gang (who misunderstand his \"rad\" as other words). Shaggy has to complete the rest of the escape on sheer guts, and with some help from Tex and his biker friends. The remorseful Svankmajer and Winsor are arrested, but Velma says she will date Winsor again when he gets out of jail, which he happily agrees with.\n\nThey then go back to La Serena Spa and Mr. Hubley tries to un-hypnotize Shaggy, but accidentally makes the entire gang turn into him. The end of the movie shows them driving away in the \"Mustard\" Machine. A post-credits scene reveals the \"Mustard\" Machine wearing a wig that looks like Shaggy's hairstyle. The GPS inside the van says aloud that if it had hands, it would remove the wig, but as such, it has none.\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Frank Welker]] as [[Scooby-Doo (character)|Scooby-Doo]], [[Fred Jones (Scooby-Doo)|Fred Jones]] and misc. bikers\n* [[Matthew Lillard]] as [[Shaggy Rogers]] and Shaky Joe\n* [[Mindy Cohn]] as [[Velma Dinkley]]\n* [[Grey DeLisle]] as [[Daphne Blake]]\n* [[Cathy Cavadini]] as Faith\n* [[John DiMaggio]] as Fritz, GPS and misc. bikers\n* [[Michael Gough (voice actor)|Michael Gough]] as Mr. Babbit, Blair, Grad Student #1 and misc. bikers\n* [[Matthew Gray Gubler]] as Winsor\n* [[Finola Hughes]] as Professor Svankmajer\n* [[Maulik Pancholy]] as Doctor\n* [[Kevin Michael Richardson]] as Tex, Cop #2, Grad Student #3 and misc. bikers\n* [[Fred Willard]] as Mr. Hubley\n* [[Dave Wittenberg]] as Cop #1, Grad Student #2, Policeman and misc. bikers\n* [[Gwendoline Yeo]] as Ms. Fetich\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquote}}\n* {{IMDb title|1777608}}\n\n{{Scooby-Doo}}\n{{Warner Bros. animation and comics}}\n\n[[Category:2011 television films]]\n[[Category:2011 animated films]]\n[[Category:2011 films]]\n[[Category:Scooby-Doo direct-to-video animated films]]\n[[Category:Animated films about dinosaurs]]\n[[Category:American television films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:2010s American animated films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Ethan Spaulding]]\n[[Category:American children's animated comedy films]]\n[[Category:Internet memes introduced in 2017]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox television\n| show_name            = Scooby-Doo! Legend of the Phantosaur\n| image                = Scooby-Doo! Legend of the Phantosaur.png\n| image_size           = \n| image_alt            = \n| caption              = DVD Cover\n| genre                = \n| creator              = \n| based_on             = {{Based on|''[[Scooby-Doo]]''|[[Joe Ruby]] and [[Ken Spears]]}}\n| writer               = [[Doug Langdale]]\n| screenplay           = \n| story                = \n| director             = [[Ethan Spaulding]]\n| starring             = {{unbulleted list|[[Frank Welker]]|[[Matthew Lillard]]|[[Mindy Cohn]]|[[Grey DeLisle]]|[[Cathy Cavadini]]|[[John DiMaggio]]|[[Michael Gough (voice actor)|Michael Gough]]|[[Matthew Gray Gubler]]|[[Finola Hughes]]|[[Maulik Pancholy]]|[[Kevin Michael Richardson]]|[[Fred Willard]]|[[Dave Wittenberg]]|[[Gwendoline Yeo]]}}\n| narrated             = \n| theme_music_composer = [[Robert J. Kral]]\n| country              = United States\n| language             = English\n| num_episodes         = \n| producer             = [[Spike Brandt]]<br />[[Tony Cervone]]\n| editor               = Damon P. Yoches\n| cinematography       = \n| runtime              = 75 minutes<ref name=\"amazon.com\"/>\n| company              = [[Warner Bros. Animation]]\n| distributor          = [[Warner Home Video]] (DVD)<br />[[Warner Bros. Television]] (TV)\n| budget               = \n| network              = [[Cartoon Network]]\n| first_aired          = {{Film date|TV=y|2011|9|6}}<ref name=\"amazon.com\"/>\n| last_aired           = \n| website              = \n}}\n'''''Scooby-Doo! Legend of the Phantosaur''''' is a 2011 [[direct-to-DVD]] [[animation|animated]] [[comedy film|comedy]] [[mystery film]]; the sixteenth direct-to-video movie based upon the ''[[Scooby-Doo]]'' [[Saturday morning cartoon]]s, the film was released on September 6, 2011.<ref name=\"amazon.com\">{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/dp/B0055HK7D8|title=Amazon.com: Scooby-Doo! Legend of the Phantosaur|author=|date=|work=amazon.com}}</ref> It premiered on Cartoon Network on September 3, 2011.\n\n==Plot==\nThe Mystery Inc. gang travels to a remote town to stay at the La Serena Spa in New Mexico, to relax Shaggy after a scary experience in a haunted mansion left him screaming for a few hours afterward. There, they meet Mr. Hubley, who works at the spa. When Shaggy asks if there is anything to eat, Hubley says no, but there is a barbecue in town.\n\nThe gang goes to the barbecue, and all but Shaggy and Scooby-Doo go off to see the paleontological dig of Professor Svankmajer. Shaggy and Scooby are too full to walk right away. When they set out, a [[gila monster]] steals a biscuit from them, causing Scooby to go after it. He meets the Phantosaur (described as somewhat resembling an ''[[Appalachiosaurus]]'' by Professor Svankmajer) and runs away. Later, Shaggy and Scooby are chased by the Phantosaur and narrowly escape.\n\nMeanwhile, Professor Svankmajor shows the rest of the gang over the dig, and Velma meets Svankmajor's student, Winsor. She instantly sees him as a soul mate and they plan to go out on a date, to which Fred replies to Daphne, \"On our own for clue searching then.\"\n\nBack at the spa, Shaggy is in terrible shape after a fright. Mr. Hubley helps with aromatherapy, assisted by Scooby-Doo adding a Scooby Snack to the aromas. Shaggy becomes more calm, but freaks out again when Mr. Hubley tells them the legend of the Phantosaur, the ghost of a predatory dinosaur. The legend says the Phantosaur was summoned by Native Americans to drive out Spanish conquistadors, but it turned on them instead.\n\nHubley has an advanced hypnosis machine with a hologram projector. He hypnotizes Shaggy to become fearless and unstoppable when he heard the word \"bad,\" and to switch back to normal when he hears it again. Then he orders Shaggy to forget everything; unfortunately, Hubley himself is affected by the hypnosis and he can't remember the key word for Shaggy.\n\nDaphne, Fred, and Velma go back to the dig to look for clues, but Velma is so love struck that she's not much use. She misses an obvious clue about many footprints going to a part of the cave where Winsor says they never go because of the snakes that lurk in the lower cave levels.\n\nMeanwhile, Scooby and Shaggy go to an all-you-can-eat restaurant and start to eat it out of business. Then a biker gang comes in. Shaggy accidentally squirts the contents of a [[hot dog bun]] on one of the bikers, who angrily grabs him and tells him, \"Little buddy, this is gonna be bad.\" Suddenly, Shaggy is fearless. He knocks out the whole motorcycle gang and repels all their assaults on him. Then the gang leader, a large, muscly man named Tex, arrives and, taking an admitted liking to Shaggy, challenges him to a motorcycle race on Dead Man's curve. Shaggy confidently accepts, even though he's never ridden a motorcycle before. As Tex leaves the restaurant, he tells Shaggy that he won't kill Shaggy \"too bad.\". Suddenly back to normal, Shaggy is terrified of the challenge he has just accepted, and by what he has just done to the rest of the gang.\n\nThat night, Daphne decides to give him motorcycling lessons, because she drove a motorcycle when she was five. Shaggy and Tex have their motorcycle race as planned, and Shaggy hears \"bad\" just in time and almost wins, until a Phantosaur shows up and he thinks in his mind that the monster must think it's so \"bad,\" which is enough to make him cowardly again and get chased, but still miraculously wins the race.\n\nEventually, they figure out that there were two phantosaurs and they were robots. The culprits were two mining engineers who wanted the silver they found in the area, which they couldn't get to because of the paleontologists.\n\nOnce back at Hubley's they find the hologram projector gone and they get attacked by a pack of ''[[Velociraptor]]'' and a ghostly fire-breathing ''[[Tyrannosaurus]]''. They learn that it was Professor Svankmajer and Winsor, much to Velma's dismay. They had found a complete ''[[Allosaurus]]'' encased in quartz crystal, a beautiful and priceless find, and they wanted to keep it for themselves. They wanted to scare everyone off so they could dig it out and take it away. They disguised three other graduate students in velociraptor costumes, and created an original red Phantosaur with an advanced holographic projector (stolen from Hubley's hypnotism room) and paint-stripper devices that blasted super-heated air for the fire effects.\n\nWhile they are underground, the dynamite charges Svankmajor set to blast free the dinosaur crystal go off (because Daphne left a paint-stripper on and the heat lit the fuses). Shaggy's hypnotic bravery comes in again when Svankmejer comments on how \"bad\" the lower caverns are, and he flawlessly leads them toward the exit until Daphne praises him that he's \"not bad.\"  Scooby realizes the keyword but is unable to tell the rest of the gang (who misunderstand his \"rad\" as other words). Shaggy has to complete the rest of the escape on sheer guts, and with some help from Tex and his biker friends. The remorseful Svankmajer and Winsor are arrested, but Velma says she will date Winsor again when he gets out of jail, which he happily agrees with.\n\nThey then go back to La Serena Spa and Mr. Hubley tries to un-hypnotize Shaggy, but accidentally makes the entire gang turn into him. The end of the movie shows them driving away in the \"Mustard\" Machine. A post-credits scene reveals the \"Mustard\" Machine wearing a wig that looks like Shaggy's hairstyle. The GPS inside the van says aloud that if it had hands, it would remove the wig, but as such, it has none.\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Frank Welker]] as [[Scooby-Doo (character)|Scooby-Doo]], [[Fred Jones (Scooby-Doo)|Fred Jones]] and misc. bikers\n* [[Matthew Lillard]] as [[Shaggy Rogers]] and Shaky Joe\n* [[Mindy Cohn]] as [[Velma Dinkley]]\n* [[Grey DeLisle]] as [[Daphne Blake]]\n* [[Cathy Cavadini]] as Faith\n* [[John DiMaggio]] as Fritz, GPS and misc. bikers\n* [[Michael Gough (voice actor)|Michael Gough]] as Mr. Babbit, Blair, Grad Student #1 and misc. bikers\n* [[Matthew Gray Gubler]] as Winsor\n* [[Finola Hughes]] as Professor Svankmajer\n* [[Maulik Pancholy]] as Doctor\n* [[Kevin Michael Richardson]] as Tex, Cop #2, Grad Student #3 and misc. bikers\n* [[Fred Willard]] as Mr. Hubley\n* [[Dave Wittenberg]] as Cop #1, Grad Student #2, Policeman and misc. bikers\n* [[Gwendoline Yeo]] as Ms. Fetich\n\n==Ultra Instinct Shaggy meme==\nOn October 12, 2017, a [[YouTube]] user named \"Midya\" created a video featuring Shaggy fighting a biker gang in the film called \"Ultra Instinct Shaggy\" using the Ky\u016bkyoku no Battle theme from the ''[[Dragon Ball Super]]'' anime and slow-motion to make the character seem as if he were in the Ultra Instinct form (a powered up state in the Dragon Ball series where the user can react to attacks almost instinctively). The video earned millions of views and spawned the \"Ultra Instinct Shaggy\" meme depicting Shaggy Rogers as an omnipotent power, with subsequent fan art showing him beating other fictional characters such as [[Marvel Comics]] character [[Thanos]] and [[Goku]] from the ''[[Dragon Ball]]'' franchise, as well as using still images and footage of the behind the scenes look at the [[Scooby-Doo (film)|2002 ''Scooby-Doo'' film]] with fake subtitles to make it seem as if Shaggy is a powerful being.\n\nAt the same time as the meme gained popularity in January 2019, the then-upcoming video game ''[[Mortal Kombat 11]]'' was being marketed and thus a petition was made on [[Change.org]] by Woken News Network to include the character as [[Downloadable content|DLC]]. The petition received hundreds of thousands of signatures even gaining attention of ''[[Mortal Kombat]]'' co-creator [[Ed Boon]], and Shaggy's voice actor [[Matthew Lillard]]. Lillard had previously tweeted posts and retweeted fan art in support of the idea as well as Boon jokingly petitioning to get [[Scooby-Doo (character)|Scooby Doo]] into another [[NetherRealm Studios]] game ''[[Injustice 2]]''. It was later confirmed that Shaggy would never appear in any Mortal Kombat game.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.polygon.com/2019/1/28/18201001/powerful-shaggy-meme-timeline-explained|title=What is the Ultra Instinct Shaggy meme?: an investigation|last=Radulovic|first=Petrana|work=Polygon|date=January 29, 2019|access-date=February 4, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://gamerant.com/mortal-kombat-11-shaggy-ed-boon-response/|title=Mortal Kombat 11 Director Ed Boon Responds to Shaggy Petition|last=Cooper|first=Dalton|work=Game Rant|date=January 28, 2019|access-date=February 4, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://comicbook.com/gaming/01/30/-mortal-kombat-11-producer-scooby-doo-injustice-2-petition/|title='Mortal Kombat 11's' Ed Boon Has Fun With Shaggy Rumours, Suggests New Character for 'Injustice 2'|last=Workman|first=Robert|work=Comicbook.com|date=January 30, 2010|access-date=February 4, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.buzzfeed.com/andyneuenschwander/|title=This \"Powerful Shaggy\" Meme Is So Damn Funny That Now Matthew Lillard Is On Board|last=Golder|first=Andy|work=[[Buzzfeed News]]|date=January 30, 2019|access-date=February 4, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://screenrant.com/mortal-kombat-shaggy-ed-boon/|title=Mortal Kombat 11 Co-Creator Fuels Fire of Shaggy Meme|last=Burks|first=Robin|work=Screen Rant|date=February 1, 2019|access-date=February 4, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://wegotthiscovered.com/gaming/petition-add-shaggy-mortal-kombat-11-got-300000-signatures-counting|title=Petition to Add Shaggy to Mortal Kombat 11 Hits 300,000 Signatures|last=James|first=David|work=We Got This Covered|date=February 3, 2019|access-date=February 4, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquote}}\n* {{IMDb title|1777608}}\n\n{{Scooby-Doo}}\n{{Warner Bros. animation and comics}}\n\n[[Category:2011 television films]]\n[[Category:2011 animated films]]\n[[Category:2011 films]]\n[[Category:Scooby-Doo direct-to-video animated films]]\n[[Category:Animated films about dinosaurs]]\n[[Category:American television films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:2010s American animated films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Ethan Spaulding]]\n[[Category:American children's animated comedy films]]\n[[Category:Internet memes introduced in 2017]]\n", "name_user": "2600:6c50:757f:bcf1:84ad:a370:2573:96e6", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(stupid nonsense)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Scooby-Doo!_Legend_of_the_Phantosaur"}
{"title_page": "Awards and decorations of the United States Army", "text_new": "'''Awards and decorations of the United States Army''' are those [[Awards and decorations of the United States military|military awards including decorations]] which are issued to members of the [[United States Army]] under the authority of the [[Secretary of the Army]].  Together with [[Badges of the United States Army|military badges]] such awards provide an outward display of a service member's accomplishments.\n\nThe first recognized medals of the U.S. Army appeared during the [[American Civil War]] and were generally issued by local commanders on an unofficial basis.  The [[Medal of Honor]] was the first award to be established in regulations as a permanent Army decoration, complete with benefits.  The Medal of Honor is the only Civil War era award which has survived as a decoration into the modern age.\n\nFurthermore, the U.S. Army mandates that all unit awards will be worn separate from individual awards on the opposite side of a military uniform.  The Army is the only service to require this separation between unit and individual decorations.  All Army unit awards are worn enclosed in a [[gold frame]].\n\n==History==\nThe [[Spanish\u2013American War]] was the first widespread award of [[campaign medal]]s, both for service in the actual conflict and for participation in subsequent garrison and occupation duty. After the Spanish\u2013American War, however, medals in the U.S. Army fell into disuse and, apart from a few peacetime Medal of Honor decorations, two medals for service in Mexico, or on the border, during the period 1911\u201317, plus the [[Civil War Campaign Medal]] and the [[Indian Campaign Medal]], both finally authorized in 1907, there were no further Army decorations created until the [[First World War]].\n\nWorld War I saw the first widespread distribution of medals for combat, as the Medal of Honor returned awarded for bravery in battle against an enemy force. The [[Distinguished Service Cross (United States)|Distinguished Service Cross]] was also created for those soldiers who had performed feats of bravery but not to the level required of the Medal of Honor. The only other medals of World War I were the [[World War I Victory Medal (United States)|World War I Victory Medal]], accompanied by a confusing array of [[battle clasps]] to denote combat participation, and the very belated [[Army of Occupation of Germany Medal]].\n\nIn the 1920s and 1930s, the U.S. Army issued very few decorations and it was often common for a service member to spend an entire career without receiving a single medal. As [[World War II]] loomed, however, an [[American Defense Service Medal]] was created for those on duty, and a [[Good Conduct Medal (United States)|Good Conduct Medal]] began to be issued to enlisted personnel. With the outbreak of the war, the Army began the largest expansion of medals since the Spanish\u2013American War as well as the first wide scale issuance of [[Inter-service awards and decorations of the United States military|inter-service awards and decorations]]. In addition, several [[United States service medals of the World Wars|World War II campaign medals]] were created for various theaters and a [[World War II Victory Medal]] was established at the end of the conflict as well as an [[Army of Occupation Medal|occupation medal]].\n\nIn the 1950s and 1960s, the Army expanded both its number of medals and ribbons, as well as having its service members eligible for several new inter-service campaign and [[service medal]]s (such as the [[Armed Forces Expeditionary Medal]] and the [[National Defense Service Medal]]).\n\nIn the modern age, members of other military branches serving under an Army command are also eligible to receive Army decorations. All Army service members may receive [[Inter-service awards and decorations of the United States military|inter-service awards and decorations]], [[international decoration]]s, and [[Authorized foreign decorations of the United States military|authorized foreign medals]]. The Department of the Army also awards a limited number of [[Department of the Army Civilian Awards|civilian awards]].\n\nThe current active decorations of the United States Army as follows (the [[Medal of Honor]], the highest military award, is not shown as it covers all of the military services):\n\n==United States Army decorations==\n<center>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" align=\"center\"\n! width=\"20%\" style=\"background:#efefef;\" | [[Distinguished Service Cross (United States)|Distinguished Service Cross]]\n! width=\"20%\" style=\"background:#efefef;\" | [[Distinguished Service Medal (U.S. Army)|Distinguished Service Medal]]\n! width=\"20%\" style=\"background:#efefef;\" | [[Soldier's Medal]]\n! width=\"20%\" style=\"background:#efefef;\" | [[Army Commendation Medal]]\n! width=\"20%\" style=\"background:#efefef;\" | [[Army Achievement Medal]]\n|-\n|[[File:Army distinguished service cross medal.png|115px|center]]\n|[[File:Distservmedal.jpg|100px|center]]\n|[[File:SoldMedal.gif|110px|center]]\n|[[File:ArmyCommMed.gif|95px|center]]\n|[[File:ArmyAchiveMed.gif|100px|center]]\n|-\n|[[File:Distinguished Service Cross ribbon.svg|106px|center]]\n|[[File:U.S. Army Distinguished Service Medal ribbon.svg|106px|center]]\n|[[File:Soldier's Medal ribbon.svg|106px|center]] \n|[[File:Army Commendation Medal ribbon.svg|106px|center]] \n|[[File:Army Achievement Medal ribbon.svg|106px|center]]\n|-\n|}\n</center>\n\n==Good Conduct Medals==\n<center>\n{|class=\"wikitable\" align=\"center\"\n! width=\"50%\" style=\"background:#efefef;\" |[[Good Conduct Medal (United States)|Army Good Conduct Medal]]\n! width=\"50%\" style=\"background:#efefef;\" |[[Reserve Good Conduct Medal|Army Reserve<br />Components Achievement Medal]]\n|-\n|[[File:Army-Good-Conduct-Medal-Obv.png|105px|center]]\n|[[File:USARCAM.gif|105px|center]]\n|-\n|[[File:Army Good Conduct ribbon.svg|106px|center]]\n|[[File:Army Reserve Components Achievement Medal ribbon.svg|106px|center]]\n|}\n</center>\n\n==Unit Awards==\n{|class=\"wikitable\" align=\"center\" width=\"100%\"\n! width=\"25%\" style=\"background:#efefef;\" |[[Presidential Unit Citation (US)|Presidential Unit Citation]]\n! width=\"25%\" style=\"background:#efefef;\" |[[Valorous Unit Award]]\n! width=\"25%\" style=\"background:#efefef;\" |[[Meritorious Unit Commendation]]\n! width=\"25%\" style=\"background:#efefef;\" |[[Army Superior Unit Award]]\n|-\n|[[File:United States Army and U.S. Air Force Presidential Unit Citation ribbon.svg|106px|center]]\n|[[File:Valorous Unit Award ribbon.svg|106px|center]]\n|[[File:Meritorious Unit Commendation ribbon.svg|106px|center]]\n|[[File:Army Superior Unit Award ribbon.svg|106px|center]]\n|-\n|}\nThe [[Joint Meritorious Unit Award]] is also a unit award for the US Army\n\n==Service Ribbons==\n{|class=\"wikitable\" align=\"center\" width=\"100%\"\n! width=\"20%\" style=\"background:#efefef;\" |[[Sea Service Ribbon|Army Sea Duty Ribbon]]\n! width=\"20%\" style=\"background:#efefef;\" |[[Non-Commissioned Officer Development Ribbon|NCO Professional<br /> Development Ribbon]]\n! width=\"20%\" style=\"background:#efefef;\" |[[Army Service Ribbon]]\n! width=\"20%\" style=\"background:#efefef;\" |[[Overseas Service Ribbon|Army Overseas<br />Service Ribbon]]\n! width=\"20%\" style=\"background:#efefef;\" |[[Overseas Service Ribbon|Army Reserve Components<br />Overseas Training Ribbon]]\n|-\n|[[File:Army Sea Duty Ribbon.svg|106px|center]]\n|[[File:NCO Professional Development Ribbon.svg|106px|center]]\n|[[File:Army Service Ribbon.svg|106px|center]]\n|[[File:Army Overseas Service Ribbon.svg|106px|center]]\n|[[File:Army Reserve Overseas Training Ribbon.svg|106px|center]]\n|-\n|}\n\n==Marksmanship Competition Awards==\n{|class=\"wikitable\" align=\"center\" width=\"100%\"\n! width=\"20%\" style=\"background:#efefef;\" |[[Marksmanship Badge (United States)|International Distinguished Shooter Badge]]\n! width=\"20%\" style=\"background:#efefef;\" |[[Marksmanship Badge (United States)|Army Distinguished Shooter Badges]]\n! width=\"20%\" style=\"background:#efefef;\" |[[President's Hundred Tab]]\n! width=\"20%\" style=\"background:#efefef;\" |[[Marksmanship Badge (United States)|Army Interservice Competition Badges]]\n|-\n|[[File:THE DISTINGUISHED INTERNATIONAL SHOOTER BADGE.jpg|150px|center]]\n|[[File:Distinguished Marksmanship Badges.png|280px|center]]\n|[[File:US Army Presidents 100 Metal Tab.png|175px|center]]\n|[[File:Drawing of the US Military Interservice Competition Badge.png|155px|center]]\n|}\n<center>\n{|class=\"wikitable\" align=\"center\" width=\"50%\"\n! width=\"20%\" style=\"background:#efefef;\" |[[Marksmanship Badge (United States)|Army Excellence-In-Competition Badges]]\n|-\n|[[File:US Army EIC Badges.png|465px|center]]\n|}\n</center>\n\n==Other awards==\n''In order of precedence''\n;Department of the Army Civilian Service Decorations<ref>{{cite web |title=Department Of The Army Civilian Service Decorations |url=https://tioh.army.mil/Catalog/HeraldryList.aspx?CategoryId=6&grp=4&menu=Decorations%20and%20Medals |website=The Institute of Heraldry |publisher=United States Army |accessdate=6 February 2020}}</ref>\n* [[File:ArmyCivServe.gif|106px|border]] [[Department of the Army Distinguished Civilian Service Award]]\n* [[File:Secretary of the Army Award for Valor ribbon.svg|106px|border]] [[Secretary of the Army Award for Valor]]\n* [[File:Army Superior Civilian Serivce Award ribbon.png|106px|border]] [[Department of the Army Superior Civilian Service Award|Superior Civilian Service Award]]\n* [[File:Army Meritorious Civilian Service Award ribbon.png|106px|border]] [[Department of the Army Meritorious Civilian Service Award|Meritorious Civilian Service Award]]\n* [[File:Army Civilian Service Commendation Medal ribbon.png|106px|border]] [[Department of the Army Civilian Service Commendation Medal]]\n* [[File:Army Civilian Service Achievement Medal ribbon.png|106px|border]] [[Department of the Army Civilian Service Achievement Medal]]\n* Secretary of the Army's Award for Outstanding Achievement in Materiel Acquisition\n\n;Department of the Army Civilian Service Medals<ref>{{cite web |title=Department Of The Army Civilian Service Medals |url=https://tioh.army.mil/Catalog/HeraldryList.aspx?CategoryId=10214&grp=4&menu=Decorations%20and%20Medals |website=The Institute of Heraldry |publisher=United States Army |accessdate=6 February 2020}}</ref>\n* [[File:USA - Civilian Award for Humanitarian Service.png|106px|border]] [[Civilian Award for Humanitarian Service]]\n* [[File:U.S. Global War on Terrorism Civilian Service Medal ribbon.svg|106px|border]] [[Secretary of Defense Medal for the Global War on Terrorism]]\n* [[File:ArmedForCivServMedalRib.jpg|106px|border]] [[Armed Forces Civilian Service Medal]]\n\n;Department of the Army Public Service Decorations<ref>{{cite web |title=Department Of The Army Public Service Decorations |url=https://tioh.army.mil/Catalog/HeraldryList.aspx?CategoryId=7&grp=4&menu=Decorations%20and%20Medals |website=The Institute of Heraldry |publisher=United States Army |accessdate=6 February 2020}}</ref>\n* [[File:USA - Army Distinguished Civilian Service Award.png|106px|border]] [[Distinguished Public Service Medal]]\n* [[File:USA - Secretary of the Army Public Service Award.png|106px|border]] [[Superior Public Service Medal]]\n* [[File:USA - Army Outstanding Civilian Service Award.png|106px|border]] [[Meritorious Public Service Medal]]\n* [[File:Public Service Commendation Medal Ribbon.svg|106px|border]] [[Public Service Commendation Medal]]\n* Patriotic Public Service Lapel Button\n* Certificate of Appreciation for Patriotic Civilian Service\n\n;Awards of unique achievement\n* Brigadier General Jeremiah P. Holland Award - awarded to the most outstanding military police unit, company size or smaller, each fiscal year.\n* Secretary of the Army Awards for Program/Project Management\n* Zachary and Elizabeth Fisher Distinguished Civilian Humanitarian Award\n\n;Regimental association awards\n* [[Saint George Award]] - Armor\n* Order of Saint Michael - Aviation<ref>{{cite web|website=Army Aviation Association of America|title=Order of St. Michael Award |url=https://www.quad-a.org/Public/Awards/Order_of_Saint_Michael/Public/Awards/Order_of_Saint_Michael.aspx?hkey=7aea8ea5-92f8-4f6a-93b6-08fc5caddabc|accessdate=10 March 2020}}</ref>\n* [[De Fleury Medal]] - Engineers\n* [[Order of Saint Maurice (United States)|Order of Saint Maurice]] - Infantry\n* Knowlton Award - Military Intelligence<ref>https://www.mica-national.org/awards/knowlton-award/ Knowlton Award</ref>\n* Order of the Marechaussee - Military Police<ref>https://www.mpraonline.org/order-of-the-marechaussee/ Order of the Marechaussee</ref>\n* Samuel Sharpe Award - Ordnance<ref>{{cite web |title=Samuel Sharpe Criteria |url=http://usaoca.org/index.php/samuel-sharpe-criteria/ |website=US Army Ordnance Corps Association |accessdate=10 March 2020}}</ref>\n* Order of Mercury - Signal Corps\n* Order of Saint Christopher - Transportation<ref>{{cite web |title=Information about the Military Order of Saint Christopher |url=http://www.tcregt-association.org/page-1291903 |website=The Transportation Corps Regimental Association |accessdate=10 March 2020}}</ref>\n* Order of Thor - Cyber Corps\n\n==See also==\n* [[Awards and decorations of the United States military]]\n* [[List of military decorations]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n* [http://www.dtic.mil/whs/directives/corres/pdf/134833vol3.pdf U.S. Department of Defense Awards Manual 1348.33, Vol. 3], dated 23 November 2010\n* [https://armypubs.army.mil/epubs/DR_pubs/DR_a/pdf/web/ARN18147_R600_8_22_admin2_FINAL.pdf U.S. Army Regulation 600-8-22, Military Awards], dated 5 March 2019\n\n{{USArmy decorations}}\n{{US Army badges|state=collapsed}}\n{{US military navbox}}\n{{US Army uniforms}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Awards And Decorations Of The United States Army}}\n[[Category:Awards and decorations of the United States Army|*]]\n", "text_old": "'''Awards and decorations of the United States Army''' are those [[Awards and decorations of the United States military|military awards including decorations]] which are issued to members of the [[United States Army]] under the authority of the [[Secretary of the Army]].  Together with [[Badges of the United States Army|military badges]] such awards provide an outward display of a service member's accomplishments.\n\nThe first recognized medals of the U.S. Army appeared during the [[American Civil War]] and were generally issued by local commanders on an unofficial basis.  The [[Medal of Honor]] was the first award to be established in regulations as a permanent Army decoration, complete with benefits.  The Medal of Honor is the only Civil War era award which has survived as a decoration into the modern age.\n\nFurthermore, the U.S. Army mandates that all unit awards will be worn separate from individual awards on the opposite side of a military uniform.  The Army is the only service to require this separation between unit and individual decorations.  All Army unit awards are worn enclosed in a [[gold frame]].\n\n==History==\nThe [[Spanish\u2013American War]] was the first widespread award of [[campaign medal]]s, both for service in the actual conflict and for participation in subsequent garrison and occupation duty. After the Spanish\u2013American War, however, medals in the U.S. Army fell into disuse and, apart from a few peacetime Medal of Honor decorations, two medals for service in Mexico, or on the border, during the period 1911\u201317, plus the [[Civil War Campaign Medal]] and the [[Indian Campaign Medal]], both finally authorized in 1907, there were no further Army decorations created until the [[First World War]].\n\nWorld War I saw the first widespread distribution of medals for combat, as the Medal of Honor returned awarded for bravery in battle against an enemy force. The [[Distinguished Service Cross (United States)|Distinguished Service Cross]] was also created for those soldiers who had performed feats of bravery but not to the level required of the Medal of Honor. The only other medals of World War I were the [[World War I Victory Medal (United States)|World War I Victory Medal]], accompanied by a confusing array of [[battle clasps]] to denote combat participation, and the very belated [[Army of Occupation of Germany Medal]].\n\nIn the 1920s and 1930s, the U.S. Army issued very few decorations and it was often common for a service member to spend an entire career without receiving a single medal. As [[World War II]] loomed, however, an [[American Defense Service Medal]] was created for those on duty, and a [[Good Conduct Medal (United States)|Good Conduct Medal]] began to be issued to enlisted personnel. With the outbreak of the war, the Army began the largest expansion of medals since the Spanish\u2013American War as well as the first wide scale issuance of [[Inter-service awards and decorations of the United States military|inter-service awards and decorations]]. In addition, several [[United States service medals of the World Wars|World War II campaign medals]] were created for various theaters and a [[World War II Victory Medal]] was established at the end of the conflict as well as an [[Army of Occupation Medal|occupation medal]].\n\nIn the 1950s and 1960s, the Army expanded both its number of medals and ribbons, as well as having its service members eligible for several new inter-service campaign and [[service medal]]s (such as the [[Armed Forces Expeditionary Medal]] and the [[National Defense Service Medal]]).\n\nIn the modern age, members of other military branches serving under an Army command are also eligible to receive Army decorations. All Army service members may receive [[Inter-service awards and decorations of the United States military|inter-service awards and decorations]], [[international decoration]]s, and [[Authorized foreign decorations of the United States military|authorized foreign medals]]. The Department of the Army also awards a limited number of [[Department of the Army Civilian Awards|civilian awards]].\n\nThe current active decorations of the United States Army as follows (the [[Medal of Honor]], the highest military award, is not shown as it covers all of the military services):\n\n==United States Army decorations==\n<center>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" align=\"center\"\n! width=\"20%\" style=\"background:#efefef;\" | [[Distinguished Service Cross (United States)|Distinguished Service Cross]]\n! width=\"20%\" style=\"background:#efefef;\" | [[Distinguished Service Medal (U.S. Army)|Distinguished Service Medal]]\n! width=\"20%\" style=\"background:#efefef;\" | [[Soldier's Medal]]\n! width=\"20%\" style=\"background:#efefef;\" | [[Army Commendation Medal]]\n! width=\"20%\" style=\"background:#efefef;\" | [[Army Achievement Medal]]\n|-\n|[[File:Army distinguished service cross medal.png|115px|center]]\n|[[File:Distservmedal.jpg|100px|center]]\n|[[File:SoldMedal.gif|110px|center]]\n|[[File:ArmyCommMed.gif|95px|center]]\n|[[File:ArmyAchiveMed.gif|100px|center]]\n|-\n|[[File:Distinguished Service Cross ribbon.svg|106px|center]]\n|[[File:U.S. Army Distinguished Service Medal ribbon.svg|106px|center]]\n|[[File:Soldier's Medal ribbon.svg|106px|center]] \n|[[File:Army Commendation Medal ribbon.svg|106px|center]] \n|[[File:Army Achievement Medal ribbon.svg|106px|center]]\n|-\n|}\n</center>\n==Good Conduct Medals==\n<center>\n{|class=\"wikitable\" align=\"center\"\n! width=\"50%\" style=\"background:#efefef;\" |[[Good Conduct Medal (United States)|Army Good Conduct Medal]]\n! width=\"50%\" style=\"background:#efefef;\" |[[Reserve Good Conduct Medal|Army Reserve<br />Components Achievement Medal]]\n|-\n|[[File:Army-Good-Conduct-Medal-Obv.png|105px|center]]\n|[[File:USARCAM.gif|105px|center]]\n|-\n|[[File:Army Good Conduct ribbon.svg|106px|center]]\n|[[File:Army Reserve Components Achievement Medal ribbon.svg|106px|center]]\n|}\n</center>\n\n==Unit Awards==\n{|class=\"wikitable\" align=\"center\" width=\"100%\"\n! width=\"25%\" style=\"background:#efefef;\" |[[Presidential Unit Citation (US)|Presidential Unit Citation]]\n! width=\"25%\" style=\"background:#efefef;\" |[[Valorous Unit Award]]\n! width=\"25%\" style=\"background:#efefef;\" |[[Meritorious Unit Commendation]]\n! width=\"25%\" style=\"background:#efefef;\" |[[Army Superior Unit Award]]\n|-\n|[[File:United States Army and U.S. Air Force Presidential Unit Citation ribbon.svg|106px|center]]\n|[[File:Valorous Unit Award ribbon.svg|106px|center]]\n|[[File:Meritorious Unit Commendation ribbon.svg|106px|center]]\n|[[File:Army Superior Unit Award ribbon.svg|106px|center]]\n|-\n|}\nThe [[Joint Meritorious Unit Award]] is also a unit award for the US Army\n\n==Service Ribbons==\n{|class=\"wikitable\" align=\"center\" width=\"100%\"\n! width=\"20%\" style=\"background:#efefef;\" |[[Sea Service Ribbon|Army Sea Duty Ribbon]]\n! width=\"20%\" style=\"background:#efefef;\" |[[Non-Commissioned Officer Development Ribbon|NCO Professional<br /> Development Ribbon]]\n! width=\"20%\" style=\"background:#efefef;\" |[[Army Service Ribbon]]\n! width=\"20%\" style=\"background:#efefef;\" |[[Overseas Service Ribbon|Army Overseas<br />Service Ribbon]]\n! width=\"20%\" style=\"background:#efefef;\" |[[Overseas Service Ribbon|Army Reserve Components<br />Overseas Training Ribbon]]\n|-\n|[[File:Army Sea Duty Ribbon.svg|106px|center]]\n|[[File:NCO Professional Development Ribbon.svg|106px|center]]\n|[[File:Army Service Ribbon.svg|106px|center]]\n|[[File:Army Overseas Service Ribbon.svg|106px|center]]\n|[[File:Army Reserve Overseas Training Ribbon.svg|106px|center]]\n|-\n|}\n\n==Marksmanship Competition Awards==\n{|class=\"wikitable\" align=\"center\" width=\"100%\"\n! width=\"20%\" style=\"background:#efefef;\" |[[Marksmanship Badge (United States)|International Distinguished Shooter Badge]]\n! width=\"20%\" style=\"background:#